article.description: Aminata Yanni scored 30 points, one of five players in double figures, as Illinois upset No. 10 Minnesota, 94-80, in a Big Ten matchup.
article.headline: Yanni, four others reach double figures
article.linkText: Illinois pours on offense in second half to upset Gophers
article.story:
CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) -- It could have been another case of bad
timing for Illinois, if not for Aminata Yanni.

	   Yanni scored a career-high 30 points and Angelina Williams added
22 to lead the Illini past No. 10 Minnesota 94-80 on Sunday.

	   Illinois lost 77-62 at Minnesota Jan. 9, three days after Penn
State defeated the Gophers 83-53 for Minnesota's first loss of the
season.

	   The Gophers (15-3, 4-3 Big Ten) were coming off their second
loss of the season, 74-71 at Michigan State, and were hoping to
bounce back once again against Illinois.

	   But Yanni scored 19 first-half points on 7-of-13 shooting to
help the Illini take a 45-42 halftime lead and held Minnesota's
Lindsay Whalen, who entered the game averaging 23.5 points per
game, to just 13.

	   "If Aminata isn't player of the week in the Big Ten, I'm going
to have a little say,'' Illinois coach Theresa Grentz said. "She
defends this kid and she scores 30. Now what more do you want?''

	   The Illini appeared to have an answer for anything the Gophers
tried.

	   "We had two days of practice that we worked on concepts of what
we wanted to do in this game,'' Grentz said. "The kids responded
very well, and we got the job done.''

	   Corrin Von Wald led Minnesota with 15 points, Shannon Bolden and
Kadidja Andersson added 11 apiece and Kim Prince chipped in 10.

	   For the Illini, Cindy Dallas had a double-double with 13 points
and 11 rebounds, Tiffanie Guthrie added 15 points and Brett Leonard
added a career-high 12.

	   Yanni said it was important that the Illini open the second half
strongly.

	   "Once we did that, we were that much more comfortable,'' she
said.

	   Illinois went on a 26-7 run in the first 10 minutes of the
second. The Illini, who were effective on the fast break the entire
game, twice increased their lead to 23.

	   "We didn't force them into having to score in a half-court
situation, that was the key to the game,'' Gophers coach Pam Borton
said. "We gave up 40 points in transition, and we're not going to
win a lot of games giving up 94 points.''

	   The Illini forced Minnesota into 12 first-half turnovers.

	   Yanni entered the game averaging 11 points per game, and had
that many seven minutes into the game. She made 3-pointers in the
opening half.
